  "title": "Venn Diagrams",
  "body": "Venn Diagrams    Illustrate set operations with Venn diagrams.    To visualize the interaction of sets, John Venn in 1880 thought to use overlapping circles, building on a similar idea used by Leonhard Euler in the 18th century. These illustrations now called Venn Diagrams.  Venn Diagrams  A Venn diagram represents each set by a circle, usually drawn inside of a containing box representing the universal set. Overlapping areas indicate elements common to both sets.   Basic Venn diagrams can illustrate the interaction of two or three sets.   Create Venn diagrams to illustrate             contains all elements in either set.   The union of two sets contains everything in either set.   contains only those elements in both sets - in the overlap of the circles.  The intersection of two sets contains the region in both sets--where they overlap.   will contain all elements not in the set A. will contain the elements in set B that are not in set A.  The intersection of elements that are not in set A and are in set B is the region in set B that is not inside of set A.        Use a Venn diagram to illustrate   We’ll start by identifying everything in the set  The intersection of H and F   Now, will contain everything not in the set identified above that is also in set .  All elements that are not in both sets H and F, and are in set W.     Create an expression to represent the outlined part of the Venn diagram shown.  Elements in H and F but not in W    The elements in the outlined set are in sets H and F, but are not in set W. So we could represent this set as   Try It Now  Create an expression to represent the outlined portion of the Venn diagram shown.  Elements in A or B but not in C    Try It Now  Let and .  Find the cardinality of each:               The cardinality of B is 4, since there are 4 elements in the set.  The cardinality of is 7, since , which contains 7 elements.  The cardinality of is 3, since , which contains 3 elements.      "
